♪ Na-na-na-na-na ♪

01:54.790 --> 01:56.000
♪ Good morning ♪

01:56.000 --> 01:57.830
As surgeons,
we dedicate ourselves

01:57.830 --> 02:00.330
to an endless fight
against the current.

02:00.330 --> 02:01.790
Jimi Hendrix died.

02:01.790 --> 02:03.330
No!

02:03.330 --> 02:05.000
That happened
kind of a while ago.

02:05.000 --> 02:07.330
No, Jimi Hendrix
is a liverless mouse.

02:07.330 --> 02:09.040
Hmm. I thought he was
a guitar genius.

02:09.040 --> 02:11.170
We're trying the seven different
polymers that I found

02:11.170 --> 02:13.250
to see if any of them can be
used instead of Cerone's.

02:13.250 --> 02:15.120
And we named the mice.
It's easier than numbers.

02:15.120 --> 02:16.880
And now Jimi Hendrix is dead
and Elvis is...

02:16.880 --> 02:18.540
Has left the building.

02:18.540 --> 02:19.920
Anyway, Hellmouth
is watching them now.

02:19.920 --> 02:21.250
You have the next shift.

02:21.250 --> 02:22.580
I mean, we really have to
come up with something

02:22.580 --> 02:23.790
if we're gonna --
-Beat Marie Cerone!

02:23.790 --> 02:25.460
No. Save lives!

02:25.460 --> 02:26.880
If we're going to save lives,
Wilson.

02:28.580 --> 02:30.420
You can't give up
that easily.

02:30.420 --> 02:32.580
It's been four days.
You can call her.

02:32.580 --> 02:34.380
It isn't easy, and Teddy doesn't
want to hear from me.

02:34.380 --> 02:36.330
Can't you just
trust my judgment on this?

02:36.330 --> 02:37.830
What are you --

02:37.830 --> 02:39.710
No, no, no, no, no!
[ Ringing ]

02:39.710 --> 02:41.540
Dr. Altman!

02:41.540 --> 02:43.290
Amelia Shepherd,
did I catch you at a good --

02:43.290 --> 02:44.500
Great.

02:44.500 --> 02:46.120
So I'm standing here
with Owen and --

02:46.120 --> 02:47.620
[ Sighs ]
Uh-huh.

02:47.620 --> 02:50.380
Uh-huh.

02:50.380 --> 02:52.670
Totally.
I would just like to add --

02:52.670 --> 02:54.620
Uh-huh.

02:54.620 --> 02:55.750
Uh-huh.

02:55.750 --> 02:57.210
[ Scoffs ]

02:57.210 --> 03:00.040
Yeah,
good talking to you.

03:00.040 --> 03:01.250
Yeah, that's not happening.
Sorry.

03:01.250 --> 03:02.790
-Hmm.
-Hey!

03:02.790 --> 03:04.670
Oh, my God, I never got to ask
you how it went with Teddy.

03:04.670 --> 03:06.250
It went great!

03:09.500 --> 03:11.620
Well, at least
it didn't go badly.

03:11.620 --> 03:13.790
[ Siren wails ]

03:13.790 --> 03:15.460
Woman:
[ Speaks indistinctly ]

03:15.460 --> 03:17.420
Man: Okay.
I'm gonna let the ER know.

03:17.420 --> 03:20.250
Hey,
lookin' good, Warren!

03:20.250 --> 03:21.540
-Feelin' good, Dr. Webber!
-Uh-huh.

03:21.540 --> 03:24.330
67-year-old female,
collapsed at an AA meeting.

03:24.330 --> 03:25.670
We bagged her,
got her breathing again.

03:25.670 --> 03:27.330
Then discovered
her DNR bracelet.

03:27.330 --> 03:29.290
-Uh-oh.
-Yeah, she was not happy.

03:29.290 --> 03:30.420
Anyway,
she asked for you --

03:30.420 --> 03:32.000
said you were
her personal physician.

03:32.000 --> 03:34.830
Hey, Richard, don't worry,
I haven't been drinking.

03:36.080 --> 03:38.670
Cross my heart
and hope to die.

03:38.670 --> 03:41.000
Ollie?

03:45.040 --> 03:50.080
So, just to be clear,
these ultrasound waves,

03:50.080 --> 03:52.290
they go right through the skull
and everything?

03:52.290 --> 03:53.500
You don't cut him open
at all?

03:53.500 --> 03:54.880
Exactly, right.

03:54.880 --> 03:57.170
The waves meet directly
on Noah's tumor.

03:57.170 --> 03:58.790
All the energy
is focused there.

03:58.790 --> 04:01.170
Imagine it like
using a magnifying glass

04:01.170 --> 04:02.620
to burn a hole in a leaf.

04:02.620 --> 04:04.250
Okay. And the risk?

04:04.250 --> 04:05.580
I mean, I know I keep asking,
but...

04:05.580 --> 04:06.830
Well,
there's always a risk,

04:06.830 --> 04:08.750
but since the procedure's
completely non-invasive --

04:08.750 --> 04:11.080
It's very dangerous.

04:11.080 --> 04:13.380
It's difficult to control
the heat that is generated,

04:13.380 --> 04:16.380
so the procedure
is slow and risky.

04:16.380 --> 04:19.250
But it's also
his one real chance.

04:19.250 --> 04:20.620
In the next few weeks,

04:20.620 --> 04:21.960
the laughing fits
are going to increase

04:21.960 --> 04:24.750
as the tumor presses
against his brain stem.

04:24.750 --> 04:28.460
In better news,
we are excellent at what we do.

04:29.750 --> 04:32.170
And we want this to work
almost as badly as you do.

04:33.830 --> 04:35.670
[ Laughs ]

04:35.670 --> 04:41.540
♪♪

04:41.540 --> 04:43.620
[ Sighs ]

04:43.620 --> 04:49.620
♪♪

04:50.460 --> 04:56.460
♪♪

04:57.080 --> 04:58.420
That was harsh.

04:58.420 --> 05:00.000
And I was thinking
it wasn't harsh enough.

05:00.000 --> 05:03.000
I didn't tell her that her son
is basically a guinea pig.

05:03.000 --> 05:04.380
Well, I'm gonna tell Kimmie
it's on.

05:04.380 --> 05:06.500
-Don't oversell it!
-Wait, is that a yes?

05:06.500 --> 05:08.080
We're on.
Okay, you know,
important decision --

05:08.080 --> 05:09.120
what are we
calling this?

05:09.120 --> 05:10.330
I'm thinking
"The Koracick Method,

05:10.330 --> 05:11.960
featuring
Amelia Shepherd."

05:11.960 --> 05:13.330
You're distastefully
cheerful.

05:13.330 --> 05:15.040
Uh, because this is
the frontier!

05:15.040 --> 05:16.960
I could scoop out brain tumors
like I'm balling melons,

05:16.960 --> 05:18.580
which is my second favorite
kind of balling.

05:18.580 --> 05:20.250
Look, we're so far out
on the edge of medicine,

05:20.250 --> 05:21.540
no one's ever
been there before.

05:21.540 --> 05:23.380
Aren't you pumped?
This is like crack for you.

05:23.380 --> 05:25.420
Or melon balling for me.

05:25.420 --> 05:29.670
Wait, where's, uh,
Bello and Blandrew? I gotta...

05:29.670 --> 05:31.670
[ Sighs ]

05:31.670 --> 05:33.290
So, this is good news?

05:33.290 --> 05:35.170
It's amazing news.

05:35.170 --> 05:37.670
I mean, look, I-I don't want to
get anyone's hopes up too high,

05:37.670 --> 05:40.210
but this procedure today
is a really big step

05:40.210 --> 05:42.830
towards getting Kimmie back out
there and singing her face off.

05:42.830 --> 05:45.960
Won't I just be back in here
in nine months with a new tumor?

05:45.960 --> 05:49.120
I mean,
it's not a cure, right?

05:49.120 --> 05:51.790
You know what, let's take this
one step at a time, Kimmie.

05:51.790 --> 05:55.460
I'm --
I'm so sick of hospitals.

05:55.460 --> 05:58.620
I just want to go back to
school, see my friends.

05:58.620 --> 05:59.960
Do the spring musical.

05:59.960 --> 06:01.330
Oh, sweetie.

06:01.330 --> 06:02.380
Kimmie,
I need you to --

06:02.380 --> 06:04.120
Did I tell you
my friend invited me

06:04.120 --> 06:07.500
to go with her family
to New York this summer?

06:07.500 --> 06:10.000
They're getting
"Dear Evan Hansen" tickets.

06:10.000 --> 06:14.120
I mean, maybe I could
last that long...

06:14.120 --> 06:16.420
[ Sighs ]

06:17.750 --> 06:20.580
Isn't this
below your pay grade?

06:20.580 --> 06:22.330
I hope you're not
giving me special treatment

06:22.330 --> 06:24.120
because
I'm your sponsor.

06:24.120 --> 06:27.670
Okay,
here's the deal --

06:27.670 --> 06:31.580
my liver has survived much
longer than it ever should have.

06:31.580 --> 06:34.000
There are multiple options
for combating liver failure.

06:34.000 --> 06:37.250
Did you see my nice fat ankles,
Richard?

06:37.250 --> 06:40.040
And my lovely
ghostlike complexion?

06:40.040 --> 06:43.670
Surely you heard it in my heart.
I have cardiomyopathy.

06:43.670 --> 06:46.290
My dying liver
is killing my heart

06:46.290 --> 06:47.710
and my heart
is killing me.

06:47.710 --> 06:50.290
I have reached
my expiration date.

06:50.290 --> 06:52.330
When did you decide
on the DNR?

06:52.330 --> 06:54.210
[ Sighs ]

06:54.210 --> 06:55.620
Eight months ago,

06:55.620 --> 06:57.750
along with
an advance directive.

06:57.750 --> 07:00.250
No intervention.
-Eight months!

07:00.250 --> 07:03.330
We talk three times a week.
Sometimes three times a day!

07:03.330 --> 07:04.500
How could you
not tell me this?

07:04.500 --> 07:07.210
I wanted to,
many times.

07:07.210 --> 07:08.540
But you know
how this works --

07:08.540 --> 07:10.750
something goes bad for you,
you call me.

07:10.750 --> 07:13.750
Something goes bad for me
and I call my sponsor.

07:13.750 --> 07:15.460
And here I thought
we were friends.

07:15.460 --> 07:17.460
Give me a break.

07:17.460 --> 07:19.920
You're acting like
a pouting teenager.

07:19.920 --> 07:22.000
We're more than friends,
Richard.

07:22.000 --> 07:24.920
I...

07:24.920 --> 07:28.330
I didn't know how to sponsor you
through my death.

07:28.330 --> 07:31.080
Good news --
you're not gonna have to.

07:31.080 --> 07:32.750
Because I'm not gonna
let you die.

07:32.750 --> 07:38.750
♪♪

07:52.120 --> 07:53.080
Thanks.
Woman on PA: Maintenance to
4 West nurses' station.

07:53.080 --> 07:54.500
Peggy, Dayna, hi!

07:54.500 --> 07:56.210
Oh, hey, Dr. Robbins.
Hi.

07:56.210 --> 07:58.080
Hey, what's going on?
Is the baby okay?

07:58.080 --> 08:00.080
Oh, yeah, she's fine.
That one, not so much.

08:00.080 --> 08:01.330
Oh, I'm a mess.
[ Sobs ]

08:01.330 --> 08:03.460
Peggy was driving
and Dayna...

08:03.460 --> 08:05.080
She puked all over me.
Like power-puked.

08:05.080 --> 08:06.210
And then I swerved and --

08:06.210 --> 08:08.000
You hit a tree
at 30 miles an hour.

08:08.000 --> 08:09.880
All the airbags went off
except for Dayna's.

08:09.880 --> 08:11.040
Ouch.
Did you hit your head?

08:11.040 --> 08:13.080
No.
My ribs feel a little sore.

08:13.080 --> 08:14.830
[ Crying ]
-It's okay.

08:14.830 --> 08:16.120
It's very common to have

08:16.120 --> 08:17.670
a release of emotion
after an accident.

08:17.670 --> 08:19.710
Especially once the body knows
it's out of harm's way.

08:19.710 --> 08:21.290
[ Laughs harshly ]
"Out of harm's way."

08:21.290 --> 08:22.420
Babe.

08:22.420 --> 08:24.420
I have
stage 2 breast cancer

08:24.420 --> 08:26.080
and I just had
my second round of chemo.

08:26.080 --> 08:27.710
That's why I got sick.

08:27.710 --> 08:31.330
So, the harm is most definitely
still in the way.

08:33.040 --> 08:34.620
[ Elevator bell dings ]

08:34.620 --> 08:36.380
Man: Uh, yes.

08:36.380 --> 08:38.210
Uh, are you sure
this is your stop?

08:38.210 --> 08:39.880
Well, maybe not.

08:39.880 --> 08:41.210
Jackson: Maybe not, huh?

08:41.210 --> 08:47.250
♪♪

08:47.250 --> 08:50.040
Sorry I haven't been
able to get free.

08:50.040 --> 08:52.920
Harriet's, uh, teething
and, you know, April's still --

08:52.920 --> 08:54.250
Please do not apologize

08:54.250 --> 08:56.830
for taking care of
the people you love.

08:56.830 --> 08:58.830
[ Elevator bell dings ]

08:58.830 --> 09:01.880
[ Clears throat ]

09:01.880 --> 09:04.120
[ Sighs ]

09:04.120 --> 09:06.120
♪♪

09:10.170 --> 09:12.460
Thank you very much.

09:12.460 --> 09:13.580
Okay.

09:13.580 --> 09:14.830
Have you talked
to her yet?

09:14.830 --> 09:16.420
I'm gonna
try again today.

09:20.330 --> 09:21.540
Koracick.

09:21.540 --> 09:24.750
April. Please, we had sex.
Call me Dr. Koracick.

09:24.750 --> 09:27.000
Um --
Um, can I talk to you?

09:27.000 --> 09:29.920
I'm -- I need to
say something to you,

09:29.920 --> 09:31.670
and it is not
easy for me.

09:31.670 --> 09:33.960
Oh. Well, l-let's make it easy.
Just picture me naked.

09:33.960 --> 09:35.540
[ Chuckles ]

09:35.540 --> 09:37.880
Tom, I, um --
what I was trying to say

09:37.880 --> 09:39.380
is that
I was horrible to you.

09:39.380 --> 09:41.750
And you were kind, and you were
vulnerable and I was --

09:41.750 --> 09:43.960
Just using me for sex?

09:43.960 --> 09:46.790
Yes, I was just using you
for sex. And I am sorry.

09:46.790 --> 09:48.290
I am sorry for that.

09:48.290 --> 09:50.420
Look, no. I love being used
for sex, Dr. Kepner.

09:50.420 --> 09:52.500
You can use me for sex,
uh, any time you --

09:52.500 --> 09:55.920
No, I didn't --
I -- No.

09:55.920 --> 09:57.830
Oh, you --
you made up with God?

09:57.830 --> 10:01.250
Well, for whatever it's worth,
uh, I'm almost certain

10:01.250 --> 10:03.540
God approves of you
using me for sex.

10:07.750 --> 10:09.040
[ Chuckles ]

10:09.040 --> 10:10.500
I don't know why
I'm so upset.

10:10.500 --> 10:12.620
Dr. Hanson told me
I'd be nauseous.

10:12.620 --> 10:14.330
Remember what else
Dr. Hanson said --

10:14.330 --> 10:15.960
stay positive, because
you're gonna get through it.

10:15.960 --> 10:17.380
He promised.

10:17.380 --> 10:18.830
Promised, did he?

10:18.830 --> 10:20.580
Yeah, he has the proof
to back it up.

10:20.580 --> 10:22.500
His success rates
are amazing.

10:22.500 --> 10:25.170
He cured my friend Lucille
without surgery.

10:25.170 --> 10:27.540
You must know him --
Dr. Scott Hanson -- Ow!

10:27.540 --> 10:29.170
-Sore there?
-Ohh.

10:29.170 --> 10:30.500
Uh, afraid
I don't know him.

10:30.500 --> 10:31.920
Oh, my God, you need to be
sending people to him!

10:31.920 --> 10:34.250
He sounds amazing.

10:34.250 --> 10:36.880
Let's get Dayna
up for a CT.

10:36.880 --> 10:38.290
And, Peggy,
we have a waiting room

10:38.290 --> 10:40.290
for you to relax with the baby,
okay?

10:40.290 --> 10:41.830
Okay.

10:43.040 --> 10:45.000
If I ever hear you
use the word "cure"

10:45.000 --> 10:47.040
and "promise" when
speaking with a cancer patient,

10:47.040 --> 10:49.540
your medical career will be
as short as you are.
Yes, sir.

10:49.540 --> 10:51.790
Call Dr. Hanson's office, get me
her medical records, okay?

10:54.460 --> 10:56.620
[ Monitor beeping ]

10:58.710 --> 11:02.000
So we monitor from
inside the room with him?

11:02.000 --> 11:04.580
-Mm-hmm.
-This is so cool.

11:04.580 --> 11:06.210
We're at the edge
of the cutting edge.

11:06.210 --> 11:08.830
And hopefully we don't
melt Noah's brain stem.

11:08.830 --> 11:13.920
♪♪

11:13.920 --> 11:15.620
[ Sighs ]
This is exciting.

11:15.620 --> 11:18.040
It's incredibly exciting.

11:18.040 --> 11:20.290
It's why we do this,
right?

11:20.290 --> 11:25.880
♪♪

11:25.880 --> 11:31.750
♪♪

11:31.750 --> 11:33.420
[ Knocks on glass ]

11:33.420 --> 11:36.170
Come on! You -- You know I love
doing that, too.

11:40.880 --> 11:43.880
"Important" isn't quite
a big enough word.

11:43.880 --> 11:46.920
But, I mean, normally, I would
take care of this personally,

11:46.920 --> 11:49.960
but, uh...she's more like
family to me.

11:49.960 --> 11:52.580
-We get it.
-Of course.

11:52.580 --> 11:54.080
Hey, you!

11:54.080 --> 11:56.080
Yeah, you, the old one.
Get in here.

11:56.080 --> 11:59.290
Uh, give me a minute,
will you?

11:59.290 --> 12:01.000
Uh, how you feeling?

12:01.000 --> 12:02.960
I need your advice
on something.

12:02.960 --> 12:06.460
When your physician
refuses to honor your request

12:06.460 --> 12:09.250
for "no medical intervention,"
what's the protocol?

12:09.250 --> 12:11.540
Do I ask to speak
to his superior?

12:11.540 --> 12:13.960
Well, I'm married to
the head of the hospital.

12:13.960 --> 12:16.880
And I mentored the chief,
so good luck with that.

12:16.880 --> 12:20.790
Okay, so I guess I'll have to
resort to more extreme measures.

12:20.790 --> 12:22.920
Mm-hmm.
And what might those be?

12:22.920 --> 12:27.040
How does "recovering drunk" go
over in the medical community?

12:27.040 --> 12:28.620
Good?

12:28.620 --> 12:32.170
Because I will
break your anonymity

12:32.170 --> 12:35.540
to any doctor
you send in here.

12:35.540 --> 12:41.540
♪♪

12:41.620 --> 12:45.500
Uh, this is Dr. Meredith Grey,
and this is Dr. Maggie Pierce.

12:45.500 --> 12:48.500
-So nice to meet you.
-The famous Meredith and Maggie.

12:48.500 --> 12:50.880
I can't tell you what it means
to meet you both.

12:50.880 --> 12:52.580
I've asked them both
to come up with

12:52.580 --> 12:55.460
every possible option
to take care of you.

12:55.460 --> 12:56.960
And like you,

12:56.960 --> 13:00.170
I trust and respect
these two women completely.

13:00.170 --> 13:03.830
So, anything you have to
share with them,

13:03.830 --> 13:06.080
you have
my complete blessing.

13:06.080 --> 13:12.080
♪♪

13:12.420 --> 13:16.670
[ Machine whirring ]

13:16.670 --> 13:18.750
Are those
sound wave readouts?

13:18.750 --> 13:20.170
Koracick: They're microphones
inside the helmet

13:20.170 --> 13:21.170
listening for
popping sounds.

13:21.170 --> 13:22.670
Sam:
What would popping sounds mean?

13:22.670 --> 13:24.540
They would mean that
his brain is boiling.

13:24.540 --> 13:26.420
It's getting hotter.
Hold off.

13:26.420 --> 13:27.830
How long?

13:27.830 --> 13:29.790
Until it stops
getting hotter!

13:29.790 --> 13:32.250
Okay, we're getting awfully
close to a cavitation event.

13:32.250 --> 13:35.040
If we go much longer,
he will develop hyperemia.

13:35.040 --> 13:36.960
Yeah, but if we don't separate
the tumor from the brain stem,

13:36.960 --> 13:38.670
he may never wake up again.

13:38.670 --> 13:40.330
-Well, what -- what should we --
-Stop! Stop! It's too hot!

13:40.330 --> 13:42.330
[ Whirring fades ]

13:42.330 --> 13:45.040
Okay.

13:45.040 --> 13:48.170
All right, th-there's nowhere
for the h-heat to disperse.

13:48.170 --> 13:51.330
This --
This could take a while.

13:51.330 --> 13:57.330
♪♪

13:58.250 --> 14:00.170
Owen: Schmitt, when I ask you
to get Dayna's medical records,

14:00.170 --> 14:01.920
it means come back
with her medical records!

14:01.920 --> 14:03.080
I'm not sure what to do.

14:03.080 --> 14:04.170
They just said
they couldn't release them --

14:04.170 --> 14:05.790
Just -- Just call --
call again,

14:05.790 --> 14:07.120
and make sure
they know it's emergent,

14:07.120 --> 14:08.420
and also make sure
they know it's Grey-Sloan.

14:08.420 --> 14:10.540
Ah.

14:10.540 --> 14:12.330
Don't take it out
on the poor interns, Owen.

14:12.330 --> 14:13.920
-Wait, what?
-I talked to Teddy.

14:13.920 --> 14:15.380
Look at this scan.

14:15.380 --> 14:16.710
I can't believe you.
What were you thinking?

14:16.710 --> 14:18.620
You double dipped
within 24 hours of --

14:18.620 --> 14:20.750
Would you just look,
please?!
Ugh!

14:22.620 --> 14:24.210
There's no broken ribs,

14:24.210 --> 14:25.620
and I don't see
any internal injuries.

14:25.620 --> 14:27.460
What else don't you see?

14:27.460 --> 14:29.880
Wait, what?

14:29.880 --> 14:31.210
Exactly.

14:31.210 --> 14:32.710
Well,
show me the sagittal views.

14:32.710 --> 14:37.580
♪♪

14:37.580 --> 14:41.080
Now, I will bet my license
this woman does not have cancer.

14:51.210 --> 14:54.040
You know, when a person's
been sober a long time,

14:54.040 --> 14:57.830
and they lose their sponsor,
it's hard --

14:57.830 --> 14:59.920
it's hard to get a new one.

14:59.920 --> 15:03.250
It's hard on the ego
to even have to ask.

15:03.250 --> 15:06.080
And recovering drunks,
as a rule,

15:06.080 --> 15:08.460
we're not all that fond
of change.

15:08.460 --> 15:11.790
But Richard will need
a new sponsor.

15:11.790 --> 15:13.380
Let's not get
ahead of ourselves.

15:13.380 --> 15:15.960
All right, we still have
a few more tests to run.

15:15.960 --> 15:17.080
Don't give up hope
just yet.

15:17.080 --> 15:19.790
Oh, honey,
I'm all hope.

15:19.790 --> 15:23.880
Hope of moving out of this old,
broken shell of a body,

15:23.880 --> 15:25.500
into whatever comes next.

15:25.500 --> 15:28.210
Hope of feeling like I did
when I first got sober.

15:28.210 --> 15:30.210
"Happy, joyous, and free."

15:30.210 --> 15:31.920
I don't need hope.

15:31.920 --> 15:34.460
I need acceptance.

15:34.460 --> 15:36.460
From Richard.

15:36.460 --> 15:38.500
I need to know that
he's gonna get through this

15:38.500 --> 15:40.120
without a bottle.

15:40.120 --> 15:42.040
Can you work that up
for me?

15:42.040 --> 15:48.040
♪♪

15:49.000 --> 15:52.540
Dr. Midvad to Cardiology.
Dr. Midvad to Cardiology.

15:53.460 --> 15:55.000
Owen.

15:55.000 --> 15:56.210
Hey. I saw you admitted
my rule-out appy --

15:56.210 --> 15:57.830
I'm sorry.

15:57.830 --> 15:59.000
Why? What happened?

15:59.000 --> 16:00.620
I, um --

16:00.620 --> 16:03.170
Owen, I want to apologize
for my behavior lately.

16:03.170 --> 16:06.170
At trauma cert day,
and actually a lot of days.

16:06.170 --> 16:07.580
I was, uh --
I was going through a thing.

16:07.580 --> 16:10.710
And I-I'm really sorry
that I worried you.

16:10.710 --> 16:12.710
Hmm.

16:12.710 --> 16:15.000
Well, I forgive you.
Completely.

16:15.000 --> 16:18.420
Because you're a good person,
April, a very good person,

16:18.420 --> 16:21.120
and you don't deserve to be
crucified for one bad move.

16:21.120 --> 16:24.210
Great. Thank you.

16:24.210 --> 16:25.620
-Sure.
-Thank you so much.

16:25.620 --> 16:27.000
My pleasure.

16:27.000 --> 16:28.750
-Hey, April, you got a sec--
-No, I'm sorry! Busy!

16:31.330 --> 16:33.040
You've got
to be kidding me.

16:33.040 --> 16:34.670
They said
their systems are down.

16:34.670 --> 16:36.500
All medical records
unavailable.

16:36.500 --> 16:37.880
[ Sighs ]

16:37.880 --> 16:39.210
Okay. All right.

16:39.210 --> 16:40.670
I'll take it from here.
Thank you.

16:40.670 --> 16:42.920
Dr. Ryan to the ER.
Dr. Harry Ryan to the ER.

16:42.920 --> 16:45.500
Hey.
I talked to Dayna.

16:45.500 --> 16:47.920
She was referred by a friend
in the exact same situation --

16:47.920 --> 16:49.380
inconclusive mammogram,

16:49.380 --> 16:50.420
and then she needed
a second opinion.

16:50.420 --> 16:52.210
And did you tell her
that she is cancer free?

16:52.210 --> 16:53.880
No. No.
We have one scan

16:53.880 --> 16:55.580
and we don't have
any of her prior records.

16:55.580 --> 16:56.830
Two chemo treatments?

16:56.830 --> 16:58.210
That really would
be a miracle cure.

16:58.210 --> 17:00.580
This guy -- there's something
really wrong here.

17:00.580 --> 17:02.420
Well, maybe she was just
misdiagnosed.

17:02.420 --> 17:03.960
Sometimes good doctors
make mistakes.

17:03.960 --> 17:05.120
Why are you
defending this guy?

17:05.120 --> 17:06.500
Why are you
attacking this guy?

17:06.500 --> 17:09.040
You have been so angry
all day long.

17:09.040 --> 17:10.500
Maybe it has something to do
with the fact --

17:10.500 --> 17:13.380
American Society of
Clinical Oncology.

17:13.380 --> 17:14.830
Yeah?

17:14.830 --> 17:17.000
Guess who is not
a member?

17:17.000 --> 17:18.250
[ Siren wails in distance ]

17:21.880 --> 17:24.580
♪♪

17:24.580 --> 17:28.670
[ Groans ]
I am tore up from the floor up.

17:28.670 --> 17:31.040
I mean
beat up from the feet up.

17:31.040 --> 17:33.000
-Come here.
-Ohh.

17:36.500 --> 17:38.540
I don't think I'm even gonna
put anything on.

17:38.540 --> 17:40.170
Oh, here,
let me get the light.

17:40.170 --> 17:42.580
Oh, yeah.

17:42.580 --> 17:45.290
Okay.

17:45.290 --> 17:47.670
Uh, here,
maybe I can, um...

17:47.670 --> 17:50.790
help sooth some of
your tore up...?

17:50.790 --> 17:53.540
[ Snores ]

17:53.540 --> 17:55.880
Ben?

17:59.830 --> 18:01.620
Uh...
[ Sighs ]

18:01.620 --> 18:06.620
♪♪

18:06.620 --> 18:09.580
[ Machine whirring ]

18:09.580 --> 18:11.960
Vitals?

18:11.960 --> 18:15.580
Stable, but the skull
temperature is spiking again.

18:15.580 --> 18:17.380
We're approaching
the upper limit.

18:17.380 --> 18:20.330
Okay, that's it.
We're done.

18:20.330 --> 18:21.880
No.

18:21.880 --> 18:23.620
I want to let it cool off again
and then do another round,

18:23.620 --> 18:25.620
make sure the tumor's all gone.
-We have to stop now

18:25.620 --> 18:27.210
before we turn the inside of
Noah's head into stew.

18:27.210 --> 18:31.580
-No, one more round.
-Dr. Shepherd, let it go!

18:31.580 --> 18:37.580
♪♪

18:38.330 --> 18:43.330
♪ Time, it takes some time ♪

18:43.330 --> 18:47.170
♪ But when that's all you got,
it eats ♪

18:47.170 --> 18:50.080
♪ At the corners of your mind ♪

18:50.080 --> 18:52.000
But we might have saved him,
right?
♪ Words ♪

18:52.000 --> 18:53.580
Well, we'll know
as soon as the kid wakes up.

18:53.580 --> 18:54.960
♪ Spoken low ♪

18:54.960 --> 18:56.080
If he wakes up.

18:56.080 --> 18:57.330
♪ Whispered quietly as if ♪

18:57.330 --> 18:59.500
Welcome to
the frontier of medicine.

18:59.500 --> 19:03.080
♪ They're in a language
only you and I could know ♪

19:03.080 --> 19:05.830
We have reviewed
every option.

19:05.830 --> 19:08.670
And, um, there are some things
that we could try,

19:08.670 --> 19:10.080
but honestly, Richard,
Ollie doesn't --

19:10.080 --> 19:11.920
Ollie has had enough
for today.

19:11.920 --> 19:13.880
So, I think
what we should do is,

19:13.880 --> 19:15.290
let's get her hydrated
overnight,

19:15.290 --> 19:16.750
and we can run some more tests
in the morning.

19:16.750 --> 19:18.790
Um, okay. Right.

19:18.790 --> 19:20.500
Uh, I'm gonna
keep an eye on her,

19:20.500 --> 19:22.540
and don't you two go far,
either, okay?

19:22.540 --> 19:23.540
Nope.
We'll be right here.

19:25.210 --> 19:27.040
Tell me you see
what's happening here.

19:27.040 --> 19:28.710
We cannot go against
Ollie's wishes,

19:28.710 --> 19:30.040
even if
it upsets Richard.

19:30.040 --> 19:31.710
The last time
he fell off the wagon,

19:31.710 --> 19:34.170
he nearly lost everything --
his career, his marriage.

19:34.170 --> 19:36.080
Um,
I can't even picture him drunk.

19:36.080 --> 19:38.000
[ Cellphone rings ]
Trust me,
you don't want to see it.

19:38.000 --> 19:39.210
Where's Catherine?

19:39.210 --> 19:41.040
In Boston.

19:41.040 --> 19:42.670
Maybe we can get her back
by the morning.

19:42.670 --> 19:46.080
Can you get on that, please?
Jerry Garcia needs me.

19:46.080 --> 19:49.620
♪ Won't let go of me ♪

19:49.620 --> 19:51.500
[ Mouse squeaks ]

19:51.500 --> 19:57.500
♪♪

19:59.790 --> 20:01.080
[ Sighs ]

20:01.080 --> 20:02.830
Jerry?

20:02.830 --> 20:04.670
We have three left.

20:04.670 --> 20:08.380
And big companies like Cerone's
always move slowly, so --

20:08.380 --> 20:09.960
For the last time,
this isn't about Cerone!

20:09.960 --> 20:11.290
It's about Olive Warner.

20:11.290 --> 20:13.460
And all the other Ollies
that we could save

20:13.460 --> 20:16.120
if we could just
work faster.

20:16.120 --> 20:18.380
Damn it.

20:18.380 --> 20:19.670
You two should go home.

20:19.670 --> 20:20.880
I have to stay here tonight
anyway.

20:20.880 --> 20:22.880
No, no, no.
I'm staying if you're staying.

20:22.880 --> 20:24.710
Me, too.

20:24.710 --> 20:27.830
♪ Deep in the ground ♪

20:27.830 --> 20:31.460
♪ Can't bury it down ♪

20:31.460 --> 20:35.580
♪ I let it go but
it won't let go of me ♪

20:35.580 --> 20:40.080
♪ Won't let go of me ♪

20:40.080 --> 20:41.210
Nothing?

20:41.210 --> 20:43.380
No change.

20:45.580 --> 20:47.790
What did we do to him?

20:47.790 --> 20:53.790
♪♪

20:54.670 --> 20:57.120
Come on, kid.

21:05.040 --> 21:07.500
[ Cellphone vibrates ]

21:10.120 --> 21:11.290
Noah?

21:11.290 --> 21:12.670
He's still not awake.

21:12.670 --> 21:14.290
-[ Groans ]
-Damn it.

21:14.290 --> 21:16.000
You just assume,

21:16.000 --> 21:17.960
since you're working with
the great Amelia Shepherd,

21:17.960 --> 21:19.750
it's all gonna work out.

21:19.750 --> 21:21.420
Hey,
there's still time, okay?

21:25.420 --> 21:29.000
Ohh. We spent the night here.
Gross.

21:29.000 --> 21:31.250
I don't know.
It's not so bad.

21:31.250 --> 21:32.380
[ Scoffs ]

21:35.290 --> 21:36.380
Oh, my God.

21:36.380 --> 21:38.000
What?

21:38.000 --> 21:40.250
I've -- I've never
been to your place.

21:40.250 --> 21:42.790
You -- You --
You never talk about your place.

21:42.790 --> 21:44.790
Uh, well, what --

21:46.170 --> 21:47.250
No, no, no!
What are you doing?

21:47.250 --> 21:48.880
No, no, no.
Sam, stop! Stop!

21:52.880 --> 21:54.750
What the hell, Andrew?

21:54.750 --> 21:56.880
Okay, you got me. I'm in between
places, that's all.

21:56.880 --> 21:58.290
I was staying
with Dr. Robbins,

21:58.290 --> 21:59.670
and then she started
sleeping with my sister.

21:59.670 --> 22:01.460
So then I moved in
with Dr. Hunt, but then...

22:01.460 --> 22:03.710
he started
sleeping with my sister.

22:03.710 --> 22:05.750
[ Laughs ]

22:05.750 --> 22:07.290
Now you're laughing at me.
Great.

22:07.290 --> 22:08.500
You're living in
the on-call room.

22:08.500 --> 22:10.460
Yes.

22:13.500 --> 22:15.250
Move in with me.

22:20.420 --> 22:22.210
A-Are you serious?

22:27.380 --> 22:28.580
-Hi.
-Hi.

22:28.580 --> 22:31.000
Hi. Arizona Hunt.
This is my husband, O-Otis.

22:31.000 --> 22:32.580
Um,
I called this morning?

22:32.580 --> 22:34.540
Fill this out and we'll call you
when Dr. Hanson is ready.

22:34.540 --> 22:36.500
-Great. Awesome.
-Thanks.

22:36.500 --> 22:39.960
Suddenly we're a married couple?
With an appointment?

22:39.960 --> 22:42.290
What happened to
"good doctors make mistakes"?

22:42.290 --> 22:44.380
His Yelp reviews
are all five stars.

22:44.380 --> 22:45.960
Well, that sounds like
a good thing.

22:45.960 --> 22:48.620
No, it's too good to be true.
People go to Yelp to complain.

22:48.620 --> 22:50.120
Nobody gets five stars.
I don't get five stars.

22:50.120 --> 22:51.750
You sure don't.

22:51.750 --> 22:54.830
So now this is your idea
and it all makes sense to you.

22:54.830 --> 22:56.580
You -- You really are
like my other wives.

22:56.580 --> 22:57.920
I figure if he doesn't know
that we're doctors,

22:57.920 --> 22:58.960
he's likely to
give more away.

22:58.960 --> 23:01.920
Hmm.

23:01.920 --> 23:03.380
Nicely done, Mrs. Hunt.

23:03.380 --> 23:05.670
[ Chuckles ]

23:05.670 --> 23:07.040
You know, I'm just gonna...

23:07.040 --> 23:08.170
You get
three and a half stars.

23:08.170 --> 23:11.290
-What?
-Same as my dry cleaner.

23:13.830 --> 23:15.790
Wow.

23:15.790 --> 23:21.670
Dr. Teller, extension 2219.
Dr. Teller, extension 2219.

23:21.670 --> 23:23.750
[ Knock on door ]

23:23.750 --> 23:26.210
Hey, you okay?

23:26.210 --> 23:28.880
I just spoke to Catherine,
and she wanted me to --

23:28.880 --> 23:31.500
Oh, so Catherine's
asking you about me.

23:31.500 --> 23:33.830
You'd like it if
Ben asked me about you?

23:33.830 --> 23:36.920
Ben Warren
can stick it in his pill box.

23:43.250 --> 23:47.670
I've spoken to Ollie nearly
every day for the past 20 years.

23:47.670 --> 23:50.540
More than I've spoken
to anyone else in my life.

23:50.540 --> 23:53.580
More than my parents,
Adele, Catherine.

23:53.580 --> 23:55.500
She's the keeper
of my secrets.

23:55.500 --> 24:00.290
She's --

24:00.290 --> 24:03.580
She's how I feel
God's presence.

24:03.580 --> 24:06.790
You've got an awfully big
village of people here.

24:06.790 --> 24:07.790
You know that.

24:07.790 --> 24:10.080
Yeah, I know I do.

24:11.790 --> 24:13.210
Dr. Kepner?

24:13.210 --> 24:14.670
Can I place an art line
in Trauma 4?

24:14.670 --> 24:16.210
Yes.
Thanks.

24:16.210 --> 24:17.880
Also, I am sorry.

24:17.880 --> 24:19.880
What?

24:19.880 --> 24:24.710
Um, I was not entirely fair
to you on trauma cert day.

24:24.710 --> 24:27.080
Your work was
particularly impressive,

24:27.080 --> 24:29.000
and I may not have made that
clear on the day in question.

24:29.000 --> 24:30.540
Thank you.

24:30.540 --> 24:32.790
I just -- I just thought
you might be, you know...

24:32.790 --> 24:34.960
I might be what?

24:34.960 --> 24:38.120
Um, you know, like,
having a nervous breakdown?

24:38.120 --> 24:39.790
Oh.

24:39.790 --> 24:41.540
Oh, uh,
I didn't take it personally.

24:41.540 --> 24:43.750
Good. Great. Great.
Thanks for that.

24:43.750 --> 24:45.580
And we will not
speak of this again.
Right.

24:47.000 --> 24:48.380
Schmitt.

24:48.380 --> 24:50.000
I'm sorry!

24:50.000 --> 24:51.540
What? For what? What?

24:51.540 --> 24:54.250
I -- I don't know.
I'm just really sorry.

24:54.250 --> 24:56.210
Uh...
apology accepted.

24:56.210 --> 24:57.120
[ Chuckles ]

25:01.290 --> 25:04.250
The truth is
we don't have any good options.

25:04.250 --> 25:05.880
We could put you on
liver dialysis,

25:05.880 --> 25:09.330
but that would cause
a real strain on your heart.

25:09.330 --> 25:11.380
Mm-hmm.
We could try an LVAD,

25:11.380 --> 25:14.500
but the long-term prognosis
is very poor.

25:14.500 --> 25:15.790
Who saw this coming?

25:15.790 --> 25:18.120
Hey, it's better to have
a chance at a good result

25:18.120 --> 25:19.540
than a guarantee
of a bad one.

25:19.540 --> 25:21.580
By whose definition?

25:21.580 --> 25:23.540
Do you think that
when I found out I was dying,

25:23.540 --> 25:27.120
I was just, "Oh, well,
that's life for you"?

25:27.120 --> 25:29.290
Coming to terms with this

25:29.290 --> 25:32.040
was the second hardest thing
I have ever done in my life,

25:32.040 --> 25:33.920
and now I'm at peace.

25:33.920 --> 25:35.580
Or at least I was.

25:35.580 --> 25:37.670
The one thing --
the only thing --

25:37.670 --> 25:41.920
stopping me from moving on
to whatever comes next

25:41.920 --> 25:45.210
is one childish, stubborn,
nagging problem.

25:45.210 --> 25:48.710
You are driving me to drink,
Richard Webber,

25:48.710 --> 25:51.750
and I'll be damned if
I don't leave this world sober!

25:51.750 --> 25:53.420
Well, if I'm the only thing
that's keeping you alive,

25:53.420 --> 25:55.250
then I guess
I'm doing my job!

26:02.170 --> 26:03.790
Please tell me
you have good news for me.

26:03.790 --> 26:06.540
My mom's Boston patient
had post-op complications,

26:06.540 --> 26:08.500
so she had to stay back
and see it through.

26:11.080 --> 26:13.120
Dr. Ryan, call the psych unit.

26:13.120 --> 26:16.120
Dr. Ryan, call the psych unit.

26:16.120 --> 26:19.040
I'm the one who's gonna have to
tell him, aren't I?

26:21.670 --> 26:23.420
[ Sighs heavily ]

26:23.420 --> 26:25.330
How do you tell
somebody something that
they already know?

26:25.330 --> 26:28.420
I mean, this isn't...rational,
it's just pure emotion.

26:28.420 --> 26:29.540
Hmm.

26:29.540 --> 26:31.710
How can I --

26:31.710 --> 26:34.330
What can I say that would
possibly change his mind?

26:36.250 --> 26:39.460
Believe it or not,
I know exactly how that feels.

26:39.460 --> 26:41.420
You do?

26:41.420 --> 26:42.920
Mm-hmm.

26:42.920 --> 26:45.210
That's how I felt
when your mother was dying.

26:50.080 --> 26:53.380
Look, I can go with you.

26:53.380 --> 26:55.170
Be there with you
when you tell him.

26:55.170 --> 26:57.750
Let me help.

26:59.500 --> 27:02.120
You helped.

27:07.330 --> 27:10.380
I have to say
how refreshing it is

27:10.380 --> 27:13.710
to have a couple
come in together.

27:13.710 --> 27:15.960
You'd be surprised
how many husbands

27:15.960 --> 27:17.000
don't even want to
come into the office,

27:17.000 --> 27:18.120
much less the exam room.

27:18.120 --> 27:19.620
-Hmm.
-Yeah, yeah.

27:19.620 --> 27:21.420
It's just we're -- we're really
close. Right, honey?

27:21.420 --> 27:23.380
-Mm-mm-hmm.
-Mm-hmm.

27:23.380 --> 27:25.620
Well, right breast
looks nice and healthy.

27:25.620 --> 27:27.960
-It's not...
-Oh, okay.

27:27.960 --> 27:30.120
...any problem there at all.

27:30.120 --> 27:32.620
Yeah,
more often than not,

27:32.620 --> 27:34.380
these inconclusive mammograms
turn out to be nothing.

27:34.380 --> 27:37.920
But, you know,
better safe than s--

27:41.420 --> 27:43.540
Yeah, this looks
slightly less than good.

27:47.880 --> 27:51.670
Unfortunately, I am seeing a
solid lesion in the left breast.

27:51.670 --> 27:54.290
Hmm. So, I...

27:54.290 --> 27:56.790
I definitely
have breast cancer, huh?

27:56.790 --> 27:58.460
Hey, uh, can you show us

27:58.460 --> 28:00.960
what that looks like
on that machine there, Doc?

28:00.960 --> 28:03.540
Yeah.

28:03.540 --> 28:07.750
You see this area
right here?

28:07.750 --> 28:10.420
And that's the lesion.

28:10.420 --> 28:12.580
And then there's a small one
right there.

28:12.580 --> 28:17.540
That's --
That is really there.

28:20.080 --> 28:22.460
I have breast cancer?!

28:22.460 --> 28:27.750
♪♪

28:33.670 --> 28:36.120
Man: Let's go.

28:36.120 --> 28:37.750
Hey. Oh, I've been looking for
you. I think I owe you --

28:37.750 --> 28:39.620
Come with us.
Right now.

28:43.920 --> 28:45.380
Did she page you, too?
Is it bad?

28:45.380 --> 28:48.670
Noah: [ Giggling ]

28:53.120 --> 28:57.580
[ Laughter ]

28:57.580 --> 29:00.500
[ Giggles ]

29:00.500 --> 29:06.500
♪♪

29:08.710 --> 29:14.710
♪♪

29:17.120 --> 29:18.250
April:
You're showing up clean.

29:18.250 --> 29:19.580
You're 100% sure?

29:19.580 --> 29:21.620
Look, they look totally clean!
See for yourself.

29:21.620 --> 29:24.120
Um, she's like --

29:24.120 --> 29:25.290
Oh, we're way past that.

29:25.290 --> 29:26.960
You're okay.

29:26.960 --> 29:29.210
[ Sniffles ]
I'm okay.

29:31.210 --> 29:33.290
He fakes
the ultrasounds.

29:33.290 --> 29:35.500
He is poisoning
completely healthy women,

29:35.500 --> 29:36.960
probably just to charge them
for the chemo.

29:36.960 --> 29:38.920
-No.
-What he does to these women,

29:38.920 --> 29:40.620
what he puts these families
through...

29:40.620 --> 29:43.790
-We need to stop him.
-No. We need to destroy him.

29:43.790 --> 29:45.830
Owen --

29:45.830 --> 29:49.210
You told me not to take it out
on the interns.

29:49.210 --> 29:55.210
♪♪

29:55.750 --> 30:01.750
♪♪

30:02.540 --> 30:04.920
You figured out a way
to get Ollie more time?

30:04.920 --> 30:06.040
Otherwise,
it's just --

30:06.040 --> 30:07.620
You know who
you remind me of?

30:07.620 --> 30:10.580
Don't care.

30:10.580 --> 30:13.920
Me.

30:13.920 --> 30:15.960
When my mom was dying.

30:15.960 --> 30:18.790
[ Sighs ]
I worked so hard,

30:18.790 --> 30:20.830
looking for anything that would
give her more time.

30:20.830 --> 30:22.170
And I didn't even
think about it.

30:22.170 --> 30:25.040
I just instinctively knew
it was what I had to do.

30:25.040 --> 30:26.790
Yeah,
but she was your family.

30:26.790 --> 30:30.420
More than blood.

30:30.420 --> 30:33.540
She shaped me.

30:33.540 --> 30:36.920
More than anyone else,
she made me who I am.

30:36.920 --> 30:38.330
How could it be wrong

30:38.330 --> 30:41.960
to do everything in my power
to save her?

30:41.960 --> 30:46.580
♪ For fifty-one reasons
not to lose our souls? ♪

30:46.580 --> 30:49.040
Because you weren't
doing it for her.

30:49.040 --> 30:53.500
♪ And it's not that
you're not the one ♪

30:53.500 --> 30:55.460
♪♪

30:55.460 --> 30:59.250
I'd give anything for
another chance to do it again.

30:59.250 --> 31:02.000
♪ And it's not that
you're not the one ♪

31:02.000 --> 31:04.330
Just to be there with her

31:04.330 --> 31:07.210
and then give her
the ending that she wanted.

31:07.210 --> 31:10.620
♪ Do you feel a little broken? ♪

31:10.620 --> 31:14.790
That experimental protocol
that I made her do...

31:14.790 --> 31:17.290
♪ Do you feel a little broken? ♪
all that suffering...

31:17.290 --> 31:18.620
putting her through
all that pain

31:18.620 --> 31:21.380
when all she wanted
was peace...

31:21.380 --> 31:23.920
♪ Do you feel a little broken? ♪

31:23.920 --> 31:28.080
...and to know
that I would be okay.

31:28.080 --> 31:32.250
♪ Do you feel a little broken? ♪

31:32.250 --> 31:34.540
It's my only regret.

31:34.540 --> 31:40.330
♪ Tell me where
we're going so fast ♪

31:40.330 --> 31:44.620
♪ Never used to run
when we were young ♪

31:44.620 --> 31:46.960
♪♪

31:46.960 --> 31:48.250
Jackson: Hey.

31:48.250 --> 31:50.040
I, uh, assumed
I was still getting her.

31:50.040 --> 31:52.500
♪ And I'm running out of words ♪
Yeah, I, um...

31:52.500 --> 31:55.290
I would really like to...
if that's okay.

31:55.290 --> 31:58.540
I -- I --
I'd really like to.

31:58.540 --> 32:00.960
How you doing?
You okay?

32:00.960 --> 32:03.420
Yes, I am --
I am totally fine to take her.

32:03.420 --> 32:04.460
I promise.
I'm good.

32:04.460 --> 32:06.080
You? You, though?

32:06.080 --> 32:07.920
You okay?

32:07.920 --> 32:10.960
Um...

32:10.960 --> 32:12.540
♪ And leave behind
what you don't want no more ♪

32:12.540 --> 32:15.080
Um...I lost God.

32:15.080 --> 32:18.750
I-I lost
Matthew's Taylor's wife.

32:18.750 --> 32:20.420
I lost her
in childbirth.

32:20.420 --> 32:23.290
And then this little boy died
for no earthly reason, and...

32:23.290 --> 32:25.580
God was nowhere to be found.
I lost him.

32:25.580 --> 32:28.830
And that's never happened to me
before, and I got scared...

32:28.830 --> 32:32.330
and, uh, really angry.

32:32.330 --> 32:35.540
And all during our marriage,
I just --

32:35.540 --> 32:37.880
I wanted you to know God
the way that I did,

32:37.880 --> 32:39.830
and you never wanted to.

32:39.830 --> 32:42.040
And so, when I lost him,

32:42.040 --> 32:46.500
it felt like, I don't know,
you've won or something.

32:46.500 --> 32:49.250
And...I hated that.

32:49.250 --> 32:51.380
♪ Do you feel a little broken? ♪

32:51.380 --> 32:53.210
I hated you.

32:53.210 --> 32:55.210
Yeah, well,
I was just trying to help.

32:55.210 --> 32:56.880
I know, I know, I got it.

32:56.880 --> 32:58.040
You did.

32:58.040 --> 33:00.460
Oh, my God, you did.

33:00.460 --> 33:05.000
Things got...

33:05.000 --> 33:07.500
really rough,
and I just --

33:07.500 --> 33:09.420
I needed to be sure
that Harriet was okay.

33:09.420 --> 33:13.790
And of course she was
because...of you.

33:13.790 --> 33:16.330
And I'm -- I'm good now.

33:16.330 --> 33:18.880
I, uh -- I found Him again.
[ Chuckles ]

33:18.880 --> 33:20.290
He and I are, like,
tighter than ever.

33:20.290 --> 33:22.670
-[ Chuckles ]
-So you know.

33:22.670 --> 33:27.500
But I realize that even when
it felt like He wasn't there...

33:27.500 --> 33:29.750
♪ Do you feel a little broken? ♪

33:29.750 --> 33:32.380
...you were.

33:32.380 --> 33:34.290
So thank you.

33:34.290 --> 33:36.830
♪ Do you feel a little broken? ♪

33:36.830 --> 33:38.960
Thank you.

33:38.960 --> 33:40.580
I'm really sorry.

33:40.580 --> 33:46.620
♪ Do you feel a little broken? ♪

33:47.830 --> 33:49.830
Koracick: Give Kimmie a standard
course of chemo and radiation.

33:49.830 --> 33:51.250
Shrink the tumor enough
to get her to summer.

33:51.250 --> 33:52.380
Amelia:
That could work.

33:52.380 --> 33:53.710
By then, I'll be able to
take the three,

33:53.710 --> 33:56.000
maybe four weeks of
vacation time I'm due,

33:56.000 --> 33:58.080
and then I'll just take Kimmie
and her grandmother to New York

33:58.080 --> 33:59.830
and we'll hit every
Broadway show we can.

33:59.830 --> 34:01.460
What's going on?

34:01.460 --> 34:03.170
Alex...

34:03.170 --> 34:04.460
Noah made it.
He's good.

34:04.460 --> 34:06.580
Noah is doing okay,
but I cannot tell you why.

34:06.580 --> 34:09.250
That procedure was like skiing
down a mountain blindfolded.

34:09.250 --> 34:10.920
We should have crashed
a thousand time.

34:10.920 --> 34:13.380
All right, hold on, hold on.
Amelia?
No, he's -- he's right.

34:13.380 --> 34:16.830
We ran into a dozen things
that we never even saw coming.

34:16.830 --> 34:18.540
And this was supposed to be
the easy one.

34:18.540 --> 34:21.170
I mean, Kimmie's tumor
is much more dangerous.

34:21.170 --> 34:23.250
Yeah, with a lot more tests,
a lot more practice,

34:23.250 --> 34:25.290
we'll be able to save
more kids with Noah's tumor,

34:25.290 --> 34:27.750
but Kimmie's procedure
is years away.

34:27.750 --> 34:29.210
-Kimmie doesn't have years.
-I know.

34:29.210 --> 34:31.210
No, no.
No, no, no, no, no, no.

34:31.210 --> 34:33.540
I do not accept this, because
you saved Noah, so you can --

34:33.540 --> 34:35.540
I will do everything I can
to make sure

34:35.540 --> 34:37.670
that Kimmie treasures
the time she has left,

34:37.670 --> 34:40.040
but I will not perform
that procedure on this girl.

34:40.040 --> 34:41.290
All right, fine.

34:41.290 --> 34:43.040
Um, Dr. Shepherd can do it
without you.

34:43.040 --> 34:44.920
Alex, I -- I'm not gonna
be able to -- No, no.
No. No, listen to me.

34:44.920 --> 34:46.460
Listen to me, okay?
Listen.
The technology is not there.

34:46.460 --> 34:48.290
Kimmie has only one chance
to live,

34:48.290 --> 34:50.250
and you are the only doctors
that can do this in the world!

34:50.250 --> 34:52.330
We're not gonna do --
I'm asking you as --
as a colleague, as a friend --

34:52.330 --> 34:54.250
Do you have children,
Karev?

34:54.250 --> 34:55.920
Please, please, please.
I will not, I cannot watch her
die on my table...

34:55.920 --> 34:58.500
-Alex! No, Alex!
-...at my hands!

34:58.500 --> 35:00.710
[ Glass shatters ]

35:00.710 --> 35:03.000
[ Breathing heavily ]

35:03.000 --> 35:04.330
Do what you got to do.

35:04.330 --> 35:10.380
♪♪

35:12.120 --> 35:18.120
♪♪

35:19.880 --> 35:20.960
[ Clatter ]

35:28.750 --> 35:30.790
I'm okay?
I'm really okay?

35:30.790 --> 35:33.500
Yes.
Your scans came back clear.

35:33.500 --> 35:35.500
Dayna,
you do not have cancer.

35:35.500 --> 35:37.040
[ Crying ]
Oh, my God!

35:37.040 --> 35:38.120
Oh, my God, babe.

35:38.120 --> 35:40.830
Oh, my God.

35:40.830 --> 35:42.460
Oh, this is a miracle.

35:42.460 --> 35:43.790
I have to tell Dr. Hanson.

35:43.790 --> 35:46.080
Uh, actually Dr. Hunt
is telling Dr. Hanson right now.

35:46.080 --> 35:48.170
-[ Sobbing ]
-Oh, my God.

35:48.170 --> 35:49.210
[ Chuckles ]

35:49.210 --> 35:51.460
Oh, my God.

35:55.880 --> 35:58.000
Hey, Doc.
You got a minute?

35:58.000 --> 36:01.620
Mr. Hunt, um, actually,
we're closed,

36:01.620 --> 36:03.120
if you don't mind
coming back tomorrow.

36:03.120 --> 36:05.710
You know, I have heard such
amazing things about your chemo,

36:05.710 --> 36:07.920
like it's smoother
and milder.

36:07.920 --> 36:09.670
Almost
makes it sound good.

36:09.670 --> 36:11.830
What's the secret, Doc?

36:11.830 --> 36:13.290
You know,
it's no secret.

36:13.290 --> 36:16.750
It's just, uh, finding ways
to make it less...painful.

36:16.750 --> 36:18.210
You know?

36:18.210 --> 36:19.250
Do I know?

36:19.250 --> 36:22.120
I guess I don't know.

36:22.120 --> 36:23.620
So, walk me through it.

36:23.620 --> 36:27.170
When you give a patient
chemotherapy,

36:27.170 --> 36:28.960
what's the process?

36:28.960 --> 36:31.170
-Uh, I mean, I...
-Let's see.

36:31.170 --> 36:35.040
So,
it comes through here.

36:35.040 --> 36:36.380
Right?

36:36.380 --> 36:37.620
No, no, no,
wait, wait, wait, wait.

36:37.620 --> 36:39.750
Wait, first --
first...

36:39.750 --> 36:41.330
No.

36:41.330 --> 36:42.830
No. Ah.

36:42.830 --> 36:44.210
Here we go.

36:44.210 --> 36:49.960
♪♪

36:49.960 --> 36:53.170
You know...Doc...

36:53.170 --> 36:55.080
I think
I'm getting the hang of this.

36:57.330 --> 36:59.290
Mr. Hunt, this is making me
very uncomfortable.

36:59.290 --> 37:01.380
I bet it does.

37:01.380 --> 37:04.580
You as uncomfortable as your
patients and their families?

37:04.580 --> 37:06.420
What's next?
What is next?

37:06.420 --> 37:08.040
Oh, I know.

37:08.040 --> 37:10.040
This is the fun part.

37:11.620 --> 37:13.540
-What are you --
-Roll up your sleeve.

37:13.540 --> 37:15.290
You're not serious?

37:15.290 --> 37:17.500
Roll up your sleeve.

37:17.500 --> 37:18.620
I'm not doing that.

37:18.620 --> 37:20.420
Why not, hmm?

37:20.420 --> 37:22.580
Why not?

37:22.580 --> 37:24.620
Because you're not sick.
Hmm?

37:24.620 --> 37:26.710
'Cause only a psychotic

37:26.710 --> 37:29.080
would pump that poison
in a completely healthy person

37:29.080 --> 37:30.750
just to make
a few extra bucks?

37:30.750 --> 37:32.120
Come on, Doc.

37:32.120 --> 37:34.170
That's never stopped you
before.

37:34.170 --> 37:35.920
[ Siren wails ]

37:39.620 --> 37:41.290
Don't worry.

37:41.290 --> 37:42.620
They're with me.

37:46.500 --> 37:47.500
[ Wailing stops ]

37:47.500 --> 37:48.920
[ Door opens ]

37:48.920 --> 37:49.960
[ Door closes ]

37:54.670 --> 37:56.420
What's on your mind,
Shepherd?

37:56.420 --> 37:58.040
[ Sighs ]

37:58.040 --> 38:01.170
What I really need is to get

38:01.170 --> 38:04.250
as far away from my mind
right now as possible.

38:04.250 --> 38:08.330
I got to admit, I'm feeling
that need pretty bad.

38:08.330 --> 38:09.380
[ Arrow Benjamin's
"Love Vendetta" plays ]

38:09.380 --> 38:12.210
♪ Oh, oh, oh-oh-oh ♪

38:12.210 --> 38:14.420
♪ Oh, oh, oh-oh-oh ♪
Come on.

38:14.420 --> 38:16.960
♪ Oh, oh, oh-oh-oh ♪

38:16.960 --> 38:18.620
♪ Oh, oh, oh-oh-oh ♪

38:18.620 --> 38:20.710
♪ Oh, oh, oh-oh-oh ♪

38:20.710 --> 38:22.540
♪ Oh, oh, oh-oh-oh ♪

38:22.540 --> 38:24.920
Really?
You brought another doctor?

38:24.920 --> 38:26.710
No, Ollie.

38:26.710 --> 38:28.920
I brought you a meeting.

38:28.920 --> 38:30.830
♪ I'm not over you ♪

38:30.830 --> 38:32.500
[ Chuckles ] What?

38:32.500 --> 38:33.620
♪ I'm not ♪

38:33.620 --> 38:34.750
♪ Oh, oh, oh-oh-oh ♪

38:34.750 --> 38:36.290
♪ Whatever I say ♪

38:36.290 --> 38:38.080
-I'm Amelia.
-Nice to meet you.

38:38.080 --> 38:39.420
♪ My heart has hit a wall ♪

38:39.420 --> 38:42.330
Um...
And if it's okay with you,

38:42.330 --> 38:45.960
I'd like to open the meeting
with the Serenity Prayer.

38:45.960 --> 38:49.210
♪ Now my armor's broke ♪

38:49.210 --> 38:50.500
Thank you.

38:50.500 --> 38:54.670
♪ Bleeding everything
that I fear ♪

38:54.670 --> 38:56.960
God...

38:56.960 --> 38:59.710
All: God, grant me the serenity
to accept the things

38:59.710 --> 39:04.960
I cannot change, the courage
to change the things I can't,

39:04.960 --> 39:07.500
and the wisdom
to know the difference.

39:07.500 --> 39:11.040
♪ 'Cause this fight was rigged
from the beginning ♪

39:11.040 --> 39:13.920
♪ All the tears I've cried ♪

39:13.920 --> 39:18.830
Meredith: All day, every day,
we fight against the current.

39:18.830 --> 39:20.710
Sometimes we lose.

39:20.710 --> 39:22.170
♪ Oh, oh, oh-oh-oh ♪

39:22.170 --> 39:23.420
Here.
Here, here, look.

39:23.420 --> 39:25.580
♪ Oh, oh, oh-oh-oh ♪

39:25.580 --> 39:29.040
It's growing.

39:29.040 --> 39:31.380
[ Sighing ] Okay.
It's growing a liver.

39:31.380 --> 39:34.420
A new liver that is
60% of normal size.

39:34.420 --> 39:35.790
So, this is Janis, right --
Janis Joplin?

39:35.790 --> 39:37.080
No, no, no,
she didn't make it.

39:37.080 --> 39:38.670
This is David Bowie.

39:38.670 --> 39:40.670
No, no, Bowie is the one that we
injected straight into

39:40.670 --> 39:42.290
without the polymer,
so it can't possibly be Bowie,

39:42.290 --> 39:43.620
because --
-Yeah, exactly.

39:43.620 --> 39:46.250
The liver cells migrated
completely by themselves.

39:46.250 --> 39:48.040
We never needed
the polymer.

39:48.040 --> 39:50.170
Are you serious?

39:50.170 --> 39:51.620
Mm-hmm.

39:51.620 --> 39:52.620
That means --

39:52.620 --> 39:54.290
We're gonna save
a lot of lives.

39:54.290 --> 39:55.790
We are gonna beat
Marie freakin' Cerone!

39:55.790 --> 39:57.750
Yes!
[ Laughs ]

39:57.750 --> 39:59.500
-Okay, stop all that.
-[ Laughs ]

39:59.500 --> 40:02.380
Sometimes we win.

40:02.380 --> 40:04.880
[ Thunder crashing ]

40:04.880 --> 40:08.120
Oh. Oh, no.
You said it was urgent.

40:08.120 --> 40:10.080
I thought I was gonna find you
lying on the floor.

40:10.080 --> 40:13.210
God, Miranda, you can't say
it's urgent if it's not urgent.

40:13.210 --> 40:16.500
Now, you listen to me,
Ben Warren, and you listen good.

40:16.500 --> 40:20.120
[ Sighs ]
I know I gave you a real scare,

40:20.120 --> 40:22.830
but you have been scared
long enough.

40:22.830 --> 40:24.710
I am not dying.

40:24.710 --> 40:28.170
My heart is strong and powerful
just like me.

40:28.170 --> 40:31.620
I'm very much alive,
and so are you.

40:31.620 --> 40:32.790
And it is urgent.

40:32.790 --> 40:35.380
It...is...urgent
that we celebrate

40:35.380 --> 40:40.330
being alive right here,
right now, naked.

40:40.330 --> 40:44.620
♪ So, you've taken
it all from me ♪

40:44.620 --> 40:46.380
[ Grunts ]

40:46.380 --> 40:50.330
♪ Will you sell me back my world
and leave me be? ♪

40:50.330 --> 40:52.040
[ Sighs ]

40:52.040 --> 40:53.120
♪ Strange ♪

40:53.120 --> 40:55.080
[ Laughs ]

40:55.080 --> 40:58.080
Sometimes the current carries
us exactly where we need to go.

40:58.080 --> 41:00.710
Oh, crap,
I left my keys.

41:00.710 --> 41:02.380
Um,
I'll be right back.

41:02.380 --> 41:04.170
Okay.

41:04.170 --> 41:07.040
♪ I bet you thought that I ♪

41:07.040 --> 41:11.880
♪ Would lose my reflection
in the sea ♪

41:11.880 --> 41:14.120
♪ You let me drown ♪

41:14.120 --> 41:15.750
April: Hey.

